== Uncodified constitutions ==\nAn [[uncodified constitution]] is one where not all elements are written into law: typically some elements, such as [[Constitutional convention (political custom)|constitutional conventions]], are not written into law, although such elements are almost always written down (perhaps across multiple documents and/or publications), although written in documents that are not enforceable in law. Approximate dates have been listed below based on fundamental founding documents on governance of the respective countries.\n\n*{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Constitution of Canada]] ([[Constitution Act, 1867|1867]])\n*{{flagicon|Israel}} [[Basic Laws of Israel]] ([[Basic_Laws_of_Israel#The_Harari_Decision|1950]])\n*{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Constitution of New Zealand]] ([[Treaty of Waitangi|1840]])\n*{{flagicon|San Marino}} [[Constitution of San Marino]] ([[Constitution_of_San_Marino#The_Statutes_of_1600|1600]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/oldest-constitutions-still-being-used-today.html|title=Oldest Constitutions Still Being Used Today|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} [[Basic Law of Saudi Arabia]] ([[Basic_Law_of_Saudi_Arabia#History|1992]]) (however, the Basic Law declares the [[Qur'an]] to be the Constitution of Saudi Arabia)\n*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Constitution of the United Kingdom]] ([[Magna Carta|1215]])\n\n== Constitutions of former countries ==\n*[[Constitution of the Kingdom of Hawai'i (1852)]]\n*[[Catalan Constitutions]]\n*[[Confederate States Constitution]]\n*[[Constitution of Czechoslovakia]]\n*[[Constitution of the Irish Free State]]\n*[[Constitution of Massachusetts]]\n*[[Constitution of May 3, 1791|Constitution of Poland-Lithuania]] (1791)\n*[[Constitution of the Kingdom of Poland]]\n*[[Sretenje Constitution|Constitution of the Principality of Serbia (1835)]]\n*[[Constitution of Prussia (1848)]]\n*[[Constitution of Prussia (1850)]]\n*[[Constitution of Prussia (1920)]]\n*[[Russian Constitution of 1906|Constitution of the Russian Empire]]\n*[[Constitution of the Republic of Texas]]\n*[[Constitution of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Constitution of Vermont (1777)|Constitution of Vermont Republic]] (1777)\n*[[Constitution of Yugoslavia]]\n**[[Constitutional Charter of Serbia and Montenegro]]\n*[[Corsican Constitution]]\n*[[Constitution of Iran (1907)]]\n*[[Constitution of East Germany|East German constitutions]]\n*[[Ottoman constitution of 1876]]\n*[[Weimar Constitution]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Constitution Day]]\n* [[Constitutional documents]]\n* [[Constitutional law]]\n* [[State constitution (United States)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Wikisource portal|Constitutional documents}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:Constitutions| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of countries|Constitutions]]\n", "text_old": "The following is a '''list of existing national constitutions''' by country, semi-recognized countries, and by [[codification (law)|codification]].\n\n== Codified constitutions (most recent, in use today) ==\nA [[codified constitution]] is [[constitution]] that is contained in a single document, which is the single source of [[constitutional law]] in a state. An [[uncodified constitution]] is one that is not contained in a single document, consisting of several different sources, which may be written or unwritten.\n\n=== Sovereign states ===\n<!-- First Constitution not the same than current constitution -->\nNote: Word counts for the constitutions listed below include contents words such as 'Chapter One' and 'Chapter Two'.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!State!!Date ratified\n!Word count<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comparativeconstitutionsproject.org/ccp-rankings/|title=Constitution Rankings|website=Comparative Constitutions Project|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{sort|Afgh|{{flagicon|AFG}} [[Constitution of Afghanistan]]}}||{{dts|January 4, 2004}}\n|10,227\n|-\n|{{sort|Alban|{{flagicon|ALB}} 