{"title_page": "Welfare Party of India", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=November 2019}}\n{{Condense|date=February 2020}}\n{{Advert|date=February 2020}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party \n| party_name         = Welfare Party of India\n| party_logo         =[[File:Welfare party of india logo.jpg|200px|center]]\n| president          = SQR Ilyas\n| foundation         = {{start date and age|df=yes|2011|04|18}} \n| website            = {{Official website|http://www.welfarepartyofindia.org}}\n| ideology           = [[Social conservatism|Value-based politics]]<br> [[Welfare state]]<br> [[Religious pluralism]]\n| headquarters       = E-57/1, 2nd Floor, Scholars Apartment, A.F.E - Part 1. Okhla, New Delhi - 110025\n| eci                    = Registered party\n}}\n\nThe '''Welfare Party of India''' is an [[India]]n political party launched on 18 April 2011. Its first National President was Mujtaba Farooq.<ref>{{cite news |title=Welfare Party of India launched |url=http://www.milligazette.com/news/1153-welfare-party-of-india-launched-politics |work=The Milli Gazette |date=18 June 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Welfare Party of India was launched in Delhi on 18 April 2011 at the Ambedkar Bhavan. It announced a 35 member working committee representing the plurality of Indian populace with diverse regions, religions and communities. There were political persons, religious personalities, Dalit, human right and social activists in the team led by Mujtaba Farooq (President), a veteran trade union leader, social and educational activist.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn June 2019 eleven dalit leaders from [[Kerala]] have resigned from the Welfare Party of India alleging [[untouchability]] inside the party. \"The Welfare Party always projected its' politics as a fight for social justice for the oppressed identities, but at the same time the dalit leaders in the party are not allowed to speak about their identity inside the organisation. This is the system prevailing in the party, it is anti democratic,\" Pradeep Nemmara, one of the dalit activists who resigned from the party, told the press. \"The party is speaking for social justice for Rohith but the party members belonging to the community of Rohith are not allowed to speak about their identity inside the party,\" said one of the members who resigned.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/11-dalit-leaders-welfare-party-india-resign-alleging-untouchability|title=11 Dalit Leaders of Welfare Party of India Resign Alleging Untouchability|date=2019-06-29|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> After the 2018 Chengannur Assembly by-elections, two dalit members of the party were suspended for four months for supporting Saji Cheriyan, the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] candidate who went to win the election. Following this, a number of party members had expressed their dissent to the state leadership and a protest letter signed by 23 [[dalit]] members was submitted to the Kerala state president of the party. \"The response to the letter came in the form of a show cause notice threatening suspension,\" Pradeep said. \"We did not go public straight away and had democratically approached the state leadership first to look into the matter. Their response was brutal and highly discriminatory. If not for speaking out issues concerning oppressed identities, then why was the party ever formed?,\" asks Pradeep. His frustration with the showcause notice only grew further as the party went on and ordered him stop contacts with the ten dalit members including his own brother who had resigned days before him. Pradeep said he was left with no alternative but to resign in the face of such shocking acts of casteist discrimination within a party that seeks social 'justice'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Known Branches==\nThe '''Welfare Party of Kerala''' is the [[Kerala]] unit of the [[Welfare Party of India]]. It was launched on 19 October 2011 at Tagore Hall, [[Kozhikode district|Kozhikode]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2011oct19/welfare_party_launched_kerala.html|title=Welfare Party launched in Kerala \u2013 TwoCircles.net|last=TwoCircles.net|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe organization argues for comprehensive land reform. Several struggles and seminars were organized by the landless people of Kerala.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2012oct10/welfare_party_workers_march_kerala_secretariat.html|title=Welfare Party workers march to Kerala Secretariat \u2013 TwoCircles.net|last=TwoCircles.net|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/land-summit-by-wpi/article18403315.ece|title=Land summit by WPI|date=7 May 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=21 January 2020|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nThe Welfare Party condemned [[2016 Indian banknote demonetisation|demonetization]] by the [[Government of India]] on the day{{cn|date=March 2020}} it was announced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/%E2%80%98Demonetisation-has-disrupted-economy-affected-the-poor%E2%80%99/article16718696.ece|title=\u2018Demonetisation has disrupted economy, affected the poor\u2019|date=29 November 2016|work=The Hindu|access-date=21 January 2020|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Hind]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n* {{Official website|http://www.welfarepartyofindia.org}}\n\n{{Indian political parties}}\n{{commons category|Welfare Party of India}}\n\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Welfare Party of India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=November 2019}}\n{{Condense|date=February 2020}}\n{{Advert|date=February 2020}}\n{{Cleanup-PR|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party \n| party_name         = Welfare Party of India\n| party_logo         =[[File:Welfare party of india logo.jpg|200px|center]]\n| president          = SQR Ilyas\n| foundation         = {{start date and age|df=yes|2011|04|18}} \n| website            = {{Official website|http://www.welfarepartyofindia.org}}\n| ideology           = [[Social conservatism|Value-based politics]]<br> [[Welfare state]]<br> [[Religious pluralism]]\n| headquarters       = E-57/1, 2nd Floor, Scholars Apartment, A.F.E - Part 1. Okhla, New Delhi - 110025\n| eci                    = Registered party\n}}\n\nThe '''Welfare Party of India''' is an [[India]]n political party launched on 18 April 2011. Its first National President was Mujtaba Farooq.<ref>{{cite news |title=Welfare Party of India launched |url=http://www.milligazette.com/news/1153-welfare-party-of-india-launched-politics |work=The Milli Gazette |date=18 June 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Welfare Party of India was launched in Delhi on 18 April 2011 at the Ambedkar Bhavan. It announced a 35 member working committee representing the plurality of Indian populace with diverse regions, religions and communities. There were political persons, religious personalities, Dalit, human right and social activists in the team led by Mujtaba Farooq (President), a veteran trade union leader, social and educational activist.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn June 2019 eleven dalit leaders from [[Kerala]] have resigned from the Welfare Party of India alleging [[untouchability]] inside the party. \"The Welfare Party always projected its' politics as a fight for social justice for the oppressed identities, but at the same time the dalit leaders in the party are not allowed to speak about their identity inside the organisation. This is the system prevailing in the party, it is anti democratic,\" Pradeep Nemmara, one of the dalit activists who resigned from the party, told the press. \"The party is speaking for social justice for Rohith but the party members belonging to the community of Rohith are not allowed to speak about their identity inside the party,\" said one of the members who resigned.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/11-dalit-leaders-welfare-party-india-resign-alleging-untouchability|title=11 Dalit Leaders of Welfare Party of India Resign Alleging Untouchability|date=2019-06-29|website=NewsClick|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> After the 2018 Chengannur Assembly by-elections, two dalit members of the party were suspended for four months for supporting Saji Cheriyan, the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] candidate who went to win the election. Following this, a number of party members had expressed their dissent to the state leadership and a protest letter signed by 23 [[dalit]] members was submitted to the Kerala state president of the party. \"The response to the letter came in the form of a show cause notice threatening suspension,\" Pradeep said. \"We did not go public straight away and had democratically approached the state leadership first to look into the matter. Their response was brutal and highly discriminatory. If not for speaking out issues concerning oppressed identities, then why was the party ever formed?,\" asks Pradeep. His frustration with the showcause notice only grew further as the party went on and ordered him stop contacts with the ten dalit members including his own brother who had resigned days before him. Pradeep said he was left with no alternative but to resign in the face of such shocking acts of casteist discrimination within a party that seeks social 'justice'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Branches==\n===Kerala===\n\nThe '''Welfare Party of Kerala''' is the [[Kerala]] unit of the [[Welfare Party of India]]. It was launched on 19 October 2011 at Tagore Hall, [[Kozhikode district|Kozhikode]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2011oct19/welfare_party_launched_kerala.html|title=Welfare Party launched in Kerala \u2013 TwoCircles.net|last=TwoCircles.net|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe organization argues for comprehensive land reform. Several struggles and seminars were organized by the landless people of Kerala.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2012oct10/welfare_party_workers_march_kerala_secretariat.html|title=Welfare Party workers march to Kerala Secretariat \u2013 TwoCircles.net|last=TwoCircles.net|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/land-summit-by-wpi/article18403315.ece|title=Land summit by WPI|date=7 May 2017|work=The Hindu|access-date=21 January 2020|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nThe Welfare Party condemned [[2016 Indian banknote demonetisation|demonetization]] by the [[Government of India]] on the day{{cn|date=March 2020}} it was announced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/%E2%80%98Demonetisation-has-disrupted-economy-affected-the-poor%E2%80%99/article16718696.ece|title=\u2018Demonetisation has disrupted economy, affected the poor\u2019|date=29 November 2016|work=The Hindu|access-date=21 January 2020|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Hind]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n* {{Official website|http://www.welfarepartyofindia.org}}\n\n{{Indian political parties}}\n{{commons category|Welfare Party of India}}\n\n[[Category:Political par